<h1>@HI{{hodo}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}}<strong>@HI{{hodo}}</strong>
<li> <em>demonstrative</em><strong>@HI{{hodo}}</strong>
<li> @Splain{{}}<strong>@HI{{hodo}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hodo}}</strong> is used to indicate an approximate amount or an approximate maximum.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{come^month}}ha,@KJ{{one^week^interval}}<strong>hodo</strong>@KJ{{nine^state}}he@KJ{{exit^lengthen}}shimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Next month I'll be going on a business trip to Kyushu for as long as a week.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<br/><br/>

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^degrees}}no@KJ{{matter^happenstance}}de,100@KJ{{person}}<strong>hodo</strong>no@KJ{{person}}ga
      @KJ{{death}}ndasoudesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Iã€€heard that some 100 people died in this accident.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<hr>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hodo}}</strong> is used to indicate a comparison. Note that when <strong>@HI{{hodo}}</strong>
follows a noun, the predicate must be in the negative.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^year}}ha@KJ{{gone^year}}<strong>hodo</strong>@KJ{{cold}}kunaidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This year is not as cold as last year.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<hr>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hodo}}</strong> indicates the extent of an action or condition by citing a specific example.

<ul>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^day}}ha,@KJ{{exertion^study}}gadekinai<strong>hodo</strong>@KJ{{exhausted}}reta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Today I'm so tired that I cannot study.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ul>
<hr>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hodo}}</strong> is used in the construction <a href="grammar-ba-hodo.html">@Vba{{}} + @V{{}}@HI{{hodo}}</a>.
<hr>
</p>

